        <h4 class="mb-3">What is a Language in Automata?</h4>
        <p>A language is a set of strings (words) made from an alphabet (a finite set of symbols).</p>
        <p>Example: If the alphabet &Sigma; = {a, b}, then some strings are "a", "ab", "bba", etc.</p>
        <p>A language can be finite (e.g., L = {ab, ba}) or infinite (e.g., all strings of any length over {a, b}).</p>

        <div class="alert alert-info mt-2 p-3 rounded">
            <h4 class="mt-0">Key Terms</h4>
            <ul>
                <li><b>Alphabet (&Sigma;)</b>: Set of symbols, e.g., {a, b}.</li>
                <li><b>String</b>: Sequence of symbols, e.g., "abba".</li>
                <li><b>Language (L)</b>: Set of strings over &Sigma;, e.g., L = {ab, aabb, b}.</li>
                <li><b>Empty String (&epsilon;)</b>: String of length 0.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h4 class="mt-4">Operations on Languages</h4>
        <ul>
            <li><b>Union (L₁ &cup; L₂)</b>: All strings in L₁ or L₂.</li>
            <li><b>Concatenation (L₁L₂)</b>: All strings formed by joining a string from L₁ with one from L₂.</li>
            <li><b>Kleene Star (L*)</b>: All strings made by concatenating zero or more strings from L (includes &epsilon;).</li>
            <li><b>Kleene Plus (L+)</b>: Like L*, but excludes &epsilon; (at least one string from L).</li>
        </ul>

